but the CLI should be sensible\nwithout the skill.\n\n## Discovery Output\n\nThe discovery command should answer:\n\n- which sessions are related to this branch/review/change?\n- which turns caused that relationship?\n- how recent are they?\n- how much data would reading them cost?\n- which agent/provider/model created them?\n- are they mostly one large backfill or incremental ongoing work?\n\nMachine-readab\n[TRUNCATED]\nai\"],\n      \"models\": [\"gpt-5.5\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\nThis is not a summary. It is an index card for choosing what to read.\n\n## Timeline Output\n\nThe timeline command should show turn-level structure before hydrating full\nrecords:\n\n- `turn_key`\n- `previous_turn_key`\n- `capture_kind`\n- `captured_at`\n- record count\n- environment snapshot status\n- observed branch/review/change keys\n- first and last record timestamps\n- maybe a tiny preview of first/last user text\n\nThis gives the next agent a cheap way to decide whether to read:\n\n- the latest turns\n- the highlighted related turns\n- the whole main session\n- sidecar/subagent sessions\n\n## Detail Hydration\n\nHydration should return ordered transcript records grouped by capture turn.\n\nFor handoff, the safest default is a bounded window:\n\n```text\nrelated turns, plus a small amount of context before and after\n```\n\nThe agent can ask for more if needed. This mirrors normal file exploration:\nstart with an outline, then open the specific file region.\n\n## Subagents And Compactions\n\nReal data already shows multiple related sessions for one branch. Some are\nsidecar/subagent review sessions, not the main user thread.\n\nThe handoff layer should not hide these. It should make them legible:\n\n- main-looking sessions: long-running, many incremental turns, latest user asks\n- sidecar-looking sessions: one backfill, review prompt, separate provider\n  session id, often created close together\n- compacted/resumed sessions: may have a new provider session id but overlapping\n  